    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Kingston</placeName>
                <date>4th Septr 1863</date>
            </p>
            <p>My dear <addressee>Mr. Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I am without any of<lb/> your favors by the steamer which<lb/>
                arrived on the <date>31st</date> Ulto. Perhaps your<lb/> letters are with the parcel
                of Occidents<lb/> which again may be in some case of <add>?</add><lb/> not yet
                opened. I leave possibly on<lb/> the <date>9th</date> just for <placeName>St.
                    Thomas</placeName>, and have accordg.<lb/> to your wishes handed over all your
                books<lb/> to <persName>Mr. Michael De Cordova</persName>, Bookseller,<lb/> who
                being in good bus<add>?</add>p, and his<lb/> shop much resorted to, will be <hi
                    rend="underline">the</hi><lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">best person</hi> to protect your interests.<lb/> I have agreed
                with him on your behalf<lb/> for 23 pCent <add>?</add> for his<lb/> labor which you
                will please confirm.<lb/> Whatever I can do for you in <placeName>St.
                    Thomas</placeName></p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>I will to the utmost of my power.<lb/> by the last accounts from <placeName>St.
                    Thomas</placeName><lb/> the Gov. Gen. Had not yet conferred<lb/> my appointment,
                notwithstanding<lb/> my election having been unanimous<lb/> and the contract, the
                    <hi rend="underline">great bane of<lb/> contention</hi>, having been carried by
                    a<del>n</del><lb/> large majority (in confidence 26 to 8)<lb/> owing to this
                petty faction, opposed<lb/> to the engagement of any minister<lb/> having complained
                to the G. G. of<lb/> some irregularity or precipitancy<lb/> in the carrying of the
                Gaul Meeting.<lb/> If the English packet expected tomorrow with the <placeName>St.
                    Thomas's</placeName> mail, should not bring the expected confirma-<lb/> tion, I
                shall still go on the <date>9th</date>; and</p>
            <pb n="2R"/>
            <p>know the reason why I will<lb/> write you are particulars from<lb/>
                <placeName>St. Thomas</placeName>. I <hi rend="underline">apprehend no
                refusal</hi><lb/> of the Gov: Gen: for he and I are old<lb/> friends and he wants me
                there.<lb/> However disappointments &amp; difficulties<lb/> may arise and who knows
                whether<lb/> I may not yet pay you a visit<lb/> at
                    <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>. You saw something<lb/> in <persName>Mr.
                    Joseph Abraham's</persName> letter to us<lb/> which you did not want to see.
                What<lb/> will you say to my informing you that<lb/> the individual in question has
                the<lb/> same reputation every where he has<lb/> been to? The Jewish Ministry in
                    <placeName>America</placeName><lb/> and the W. J. is so easy <add>?</add> that
                all<lb/> persons who can manage to attain a<lb/> learning hearing either from
                Reading Desk or</p>
            <pb n="2V"/>
            <p>pulpit obtain engagements and I<lb/> will present myself to say of the party<lb/> in
                question is that in the absence of being<lb/> able to report any thing good, I will
                not<lb/> pen any thing bad. <add>ודי לחכימא ברמיזא וד"ל</add> I have as yet<lb/> no
                acknowledgment of my letter containing<lb/> so many items of information about
                    <placeName>St.<lb/> Thomas<lb/> Curaçao</placeName>. Have you received it?<lb/>
                I beg you will on receipt of this write<lb/> to <persName>Mr. Joseph
                    Abrahams</persName>, <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName>, informing<lb/> him how
                matters stand with me and<lb/>
                <placeName>St. Thomas</placeName> at present. If my engagement<lb/> there be <add>or
                    be not</add> concluded I will write him.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Would that I could <del>write</del> congratulate<lb/> you and every
                one in the <placeName>States</placeName>, with the<lb/> words <add>תכלה שנה
                    וקללותיה</add>; but though ultimate<lb/> good must result from this
                unnatural,<lb/> sanguinary, and heart sickening contest<lb/> it is apparently so
                very remote that<lb/> many on that soil will sink into the<lb/> grave and be
                forgotten before the</p>
            <pb n="3R"/>
            <p>jubilant<add>?</add> sounds be heard <add>וברכותיה</add><lb/>
                <add>תחל שנה</add>! A former pupil resident for the<lb/> last 6 years in
                    <placeName>N. O.</placeName> arrived here a few<lb/> days back, and gave me a
                deplorable<lb/> account of the condition of my late<lb/> congregation there.
                        <persName>Gutheim<add>?</add></persName>, poor fellow,<lb/> is at
                    <placeName>Augusta, Ga.</placeName> with his wife's family.<lb/> Who would have
                thought 13 years ago<lb/> that witnessed <persName>Judah Touro's</persName>
                signature<lb/> to her noble deed of gift, or saw him laying<lb/> the foundation
                stone, that the worshippers<lb/> would all be gone from the sacred house<lb/> and
                that <add>שמיר ושית תהי כל הארץ</add>. Nothing is<lb/> certain but God, death, and
                Eternity.<lb/> Your late articles in the Occident are written with much vigor and
                    p<add>?</add>. I<lb/> read them with pleasure and profit.<lb/> Our colonial
                Jews, particularly in<lb/>
                <placeName>Jamaica</placeName> are crying out loudly of there<lb/> being no Jewish
                Boarding School in<lb/>
                <placeName>England</placeName> where they can place their<lb/> children. They do not
                like any there; and</p>
            <pb n="3V"/>
            <p>many of the British Jews complain of the same<lb/> thing. A great many would like <hi
                    rend="underline">me</hi> to<lb/> start such an establishment, but I would<lb/>
                not attempt it without <del>
                    <add>?</add>
                </del> receiving<lb/> help in money, and the certainty of<lb/> a good number of
                pupils. One thing<lb/> is certain. If I go to the end of the<lb/> world, I will no
                longer stay in this<lb/> brutalizing heart and soul debasing<lb/> spot, where the
                forms of religion are<lb/> in some measure outwardly observed,<lb/> but the
                    <add>שמעיות מצות</add>, especially as relating<lb/>
                <add>בין איל ואחיו</add>, are utterly disregarded.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Mention us to all old friends<lb/> especially <persName>Miss
                    Gratz</persName>, <persName>Miss Louisa<lb/> Hart</persName> &amp; family, and
                    <persName>Mr. Abraham<lb/> Hart</persName> &amp; family. May the prayers of<lb/>
                you all be heard before the Eternal<lb/> Throne and your names inscribed<lb/>
                <add>בספר חיים טובים מחילה וסליחה</add>. <persName>Mrs N</persName> sends her
                love.Your friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">
                <persName role="author">M N Nathan</persName>
            </p>
